   Personal Statement Stanford iGEM Paragraph
 I didn’t know I would find my passion two years before when I joined the Stanford iGEM in the summer 2024. Pathways that regulated homeostasis or underpinned physiological changes [initially/initiated] drove my fascination in biology. This program/Stanford iGEM internship program was my entry way into learning the lab techniques to characterize pathways I had loved reading in textbooks and begin to employ these pathways for therapeutics. The team’s project focused on competitively inhibiting DUX4-fl with a truncated isoform as a potential therapy for Facioscapulohumeral Muscular Dystrophy (FSHD). A difficulty with any drug therapy for FSHD is that DUX4-fl can diffuse across multi-nucleated muscle cells/myotubes and in sporadic bursts. To create a better experimental model than transfecting transiently, I helped in creating a C2C12 cell line stably expressing mScarlet DUX4 reporter by constructing DUX4 reporter plasmids with hygromycin resistance gene and using antibiotic selection to select for cells that had been transfected with DUX4 reporter. Since there is clinical variability in FSHD patients, the team also had a side project to investigate whether we could analyze MRI images to characterize FSHD disease progression and explore where and when to deliver the therapy– detected by STIR+ signals, for example–that is less invasive than biopsies. I specifically worked on researching and creating a pipeline to preprocess MRI images. I embraced solidifying my skills in Python, writing functions, while and for loops, list comprehensions, dictionaries, and then practiced implementing code to solve problems through Kaggle during my daily 3-hour commute. I worked mainly on bias correct, while gaining more experience with Matplotlib and NumPy, SimpleITK, and introduction into PyTorch, and learned the general approach to most of the steps of MRI preprocessing, such as resampling, denoising, masking, and registration by reading readthedocs SimpleITK online manual and interpreting sample code on Github. While doing the code for bias correction, I also enjoyed figuring out the math that underpinned code. For example, b-spline functions, which has to do with smoothness, degree, and knot sequences and these parameters help in curve-fitting. Discovering how concepts I had learned in multivariable calculus and linear algebra were applied to quantifying MRI images invigorates me to continue strengthening my foundation in pure math. Ground my thinking in terms of program came from math.
