   Fidler Lab Paragraph
 My experience building analytical methods in organic chemistry was complemented by being a research apprentice at the Fidler Lab investigating the mechanisms in which clonal hematopoiesis–the expansion of hematopoietic stem cells containing somatic mutations–drives atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease and role of genes on immune cells in atherosclerotic plaques for therapeutic targets. When I first entered the lab, I helped out on various segments of the research associate’s and post-doctorate’s experimental workflows in a non-sequential order, where I learned to independently figure out the order and the purpose of each experiment and ask clarifying questions when team members had a few minutes. For example, I’ve assisted a research associate on their project by conducting qPCR, H&E staining and immunohistochemistry to see whether a gene is a regulator of macrophage accumulation in atheromas. Assisting my research associate had prepared me to investigate a gene, Dmxl1, from start to finish. Efficiently completing experiments on qPCR to validate that the gene was successfully knocked out, histological staining to quantify whether the gene increased the formation of atherosclerotic lesions and present these findings, as well as the experimental workflow at the Bay Area Cardiovascular Research Symposium within four weeks/a month from starting. Although I hypothesized that CRISPR knockout of Dmxl1 in hematopoietic stem cells increase formation of atherosclerotic plaque as there was preliminary data that suggested Dmxl1 was a gene correlated with coronary artery disease from a Genome-Wide Associated Study, there was unexpected result where deletion of Dmxl1 in hematopoietic cells had no significant change in lesion area and many of the mice in the cohort were growing sick or died. My study/literature review of Dmxl1, I had found out that a previous study presented that global knockout of Dmxl1 in kidney intercalated cells was embryonic lethal, so I inferred that conditional knockout of Dmxl1 may effect a physiological needed for living. After presenting the poster, we attempted/tried a Dmxl1 floxed mice cohort resulting in similar results where the mice grew sick or died prematurely, we pivoted to Asxl1 because...Since evidence suggests that Dmxl1 is not a viable pathway, I focused on finding new ones. Drawing on my experience in organic chemistry and my work in Fidler's lab... I began learning how to fix the pathway, get it working, and tackled the engineering challenges. This is the part I hope to study in my undergraduate research program (REU). Dream to work in bioengineering, nanoscience, microfluidics. Have done a lot of preparation, equipped with skills, prepared to work in this field. Done research into this field to realize things that need to be solved. Have the mindset, mentality and the skills to be able to start working in this field to solve these problems. This is why I want to be in the program. Core theme, 85% percent, small quiz. If you don’t understand the story, he is trying to investigate or tell with this problem, framework to solve, from the get go, you don’t have the tools or thinking framework to solve the problem.
